  "prompt": "How do you round to one decimal place?",
  "response": "To round a number to one decimal place, follow these steps:\n\n1. **Identify the digit in the first decimal place**:  \n   This is the first digit to the right of the decimal point.\n\n2. **Look at the digit in the second decimal place**:  \n   This is the digit immediately to the right of the first decimal place.\n\n3. **Apply the rounding rule**:  \n   - If the digit in the second decimal place is **5 or greater**, **add 1** to the digit in the first decimal place.  \n   - If the digit in the second decimal place is **less than 5**, **keep the digit in the first decimal place unchanged**.\n\n4. **Drop all digits after the first decimal place**:  \n   After rounding, remove all digits to the right of the first decimal place.\n\n### Example:\nRound the number \\( 3.467 \\) to one decimal place.\n\n1. The first decimal place digit is **4** (in \\( 3.4 \\)).\n2. The second decimal place digit is **6** (in \\( 3.46 \\)).\n3. Since \\( 6 \\geq 5 \\), add 1 to the first decimal place digit: \\( 4 + 1 = 5 \\).\n4. Drop all digits after the first decimal place: \\( 3.5 \\).\n\n### Final Answer:\n\\( 3.467 \\) rounded to one decimal place is **\\( 3.5 \\)**.",
